{"type":"message","id":"2d8f7dac","parentId":"71fd8c52","timestamp":"2026-04-21T17:17:02.497Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, but this means the video URL is `http://103.253.21.139:5000/video/demo.mp4`. The Flask backend serves this file. The browser would be loading the video from port 5000. This might have CORS issues since the page is on port 3003 and the video is on port 5000.\n\nBut wait, Flask-CORS is set up with `origins: '*'`, so CORS should be fine.\n\nActually, let me think again. The `API_BASE` is used for `fetchAPI` which calls `fetch(\\`${API_BASE}${path}\\`)`. So for the API, `API_BASE` should be empty (so `/api/summary` goes through the Vite proxy to port 5000). \n\nBut for the video, I need it to go directly to port 5000. If I set `API_BASE` to port 5000, the API calls would work but they'd bypass the proxy entirely, and if port 5000 isn't accessible from the browser, everything breaks. The proxy setup only routes `/api` and `/socket.io` to port 5000, so other paths would fail. I think the cleanest approach is to keep `API_BASE` empty for the proxy to handle API calls, and just hardcode the video URL directly to port 5000.","thinkingSignature":"16e77b899fe7b9b7fe5083b3af4f53f725b30697a29c4cf6cd2b31fba5b73b7b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_005dc9l9q4n2_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/frontend/src/App.jsx","edits":[{"oldText":"const API_BASE = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE || 'http://103.253.21.139:5000'\nconst VIDEO_URL = `${API_BASE}/video/demo.mp4`","newText":"const API_BASE = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE || ''\n// Video: direct to Flask backend (bypass proxy for video loading)\nconst VIDEO_URL = 'http://103.253.21.139:5000/video/demo.mp4'"}]}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":77,"output":440,"cacheRead":148251,"cacheWrite":475,"totalTokens":149243,"cost":{"input":0,"output":