{"type":"message","id":"2a1328f0","parentId":"f738220c","timestamp":"2026-04-21T17:27:52.729Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try a smarter approach. Instead of trying to find ffmpeg libraries, let me check if there's a static ffmpeg binary I can download, or try to use a Python-based approach to generate WebM/VP8 video.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. I know the video doesn't play because the codec (mp4v/MPEG-4 Part 2) is not supported in browsers. The options are:\n\n1. Download a static ffmpeg binary\n2. Generate VP8/VP9/WebM using Python (if possible)\n3. Use a different approach - serve the video as a data URL or chunked streaming\n\n\n4. Create an HTML file that generates video frames on the fly using JavaScript and the Canvas API to draw animated people with bounding boxes, avoiding the need for a pre-generated video file altogether.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether I should attempt to download a static ffmpeg binary, but disk space is tight at 97% full, so I need to be careful. Let me explore if Python has any VP8 or VP9 encoding libraries available, though that would require re-encoding every frame which could be slow. Another angle is to use the FFMPEG libraries already compiled into OpenCV through its Python bindings. the underlying FFmpeg libraries (libavcodec, libavformat) through ctypes or direct API calls, but that's extremely complex. Let me try downloading a static ffmpeg binary instead, since the disk space issue might be manageable if I get a minimal build.","thinkingSignature":"8abcaa47282f63037c1110a0abdca18d0353d4f051ea59a2603ac7a4c2a801d0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qadhv3irs7ea_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"df -h / | tail -1\ndu -sh /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/ 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":56,"output":380,"cacheRead":59517,"cacheWrite":2