{"type":"message","id":"b733a12c","parentId":"d15e72e5","timestamp":"2026-04-21T17:28:01.941Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, disk space shows only 368M used, 99% full, 34G total. But the project is 197MB. Let me check what's using all the space.Actually, looking at the disk usage: 34G total, 34G used, only 368M free. But the project is only 197MB. So there must be other things using disk space. Let me check.\n\nBut wait - the disk IS 99% full. Downloading ffmpeg binary (~80-100MB) would be risky.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Instead of trying to fix the video codec, let me:\n\n1. **Generate a WebM video** using Python's built-in capabilities\n\n\n2. **Use JavaScript** to create an animated visualization\n3. **Try to install ffmpeg** via pip\n\nFor option 3, I know there's a `ffmpeg` Python package that downloads the binary automatically. Let me try that. The package is only about 5MB in Python wheel format, so it should be lightweight enough to install without hitting the disk limit.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the ffmpeg-python package just wraps the command-line tool, so it won't work if the actual binary isn't installed. Let me think about what video codecs browsers actually support and go from there. I've confirmed H.264 works, and VP8 is definitely supported, so maybe I should try installing ffmpeg through apt-get with a minimal package instead of pip.","thinkingSignature":"4ef9995a50d35118ca0d53f8342f089939ebe1db057c506433198d058a0c67c9"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_w8t5kiauai4l_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Try minimal ffmpeg install\napt-get install -y ffmpeg 2>&1 | tail -5","yieldMs":60000,"timeout":120}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":88,"output":374,"cacheRead":59733,"cacheWrite":463,"totalTokens":60658,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp