{"type":"message","id":"7435585d","parentId":"d2e73a1b","timestamp":"2026-04-21T17:32:04.331Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file IS correctly encoded as H.264 (avcC atom found, H.264 start codes present). The MIME type is correct. The video returns 206 Partial Content which means Range requests work.\n\nThe issue might be that the `<video>` element's `src` is being set correctly, but:\n1. Maybe the video element in the component is broken\n2. Maybe there's a CSS issue\n3. Maybe the video can't be loaded due to the browser blocking it\n\nWait - the user said \"video đã get được nhưng không hiển thị được\". They said the video GET is returning 206 Partial Content but not displaying. \n\nThe component structure looks right with the video element and source set up correctly, so the real question is why the browser isn't rendering it even though it's getting the file with proper Range request support. The video element might be stuck in a loading state or failing to initialize, possibly due to CORS issues if the source isn't same-origin, though the network tab showing a 206 response suggests the request itself succeeded. I should consider whether the autoplay policy, muted attribute, or play() method failure is preventing playback, and potentially try switching to an HLS stream or using a different video source to rule out format issues. The dev server might be interfering with Range requests even though it claims 206 Partial Content support. I could try embedding the video as a base64 data URL to bypass all network issues, though that would be large, or just test with the Big Buck Bunny URL that was already set up to see if that resolves the display problem.\n\nActually, the user's network tab is showing a 206 Partial Content response, which means the server is responding to Range requests—the video is being fetched, so the issue isn't the video file itself or how it's being served. The problem must be something else, like the video element might not have proper dimensions or styling preventing it from displaying visually.\n\nLet me check if the CSS is using `display: block` on the video and verify the video element has an actual width set, since a 0px width would make it invisible even if the video loads correctly. I'm going to stop overthinking this and just switch to the Big Buck Bunny URL since that's confirmed working, and maybe add a direct video element in the HTML to rule out any React rendering issues. The video element structure looks correct with the src, controls, and autoPlay attributes, so the problem might be something environmental on the user's end—let me check if maybe the dev server is actually serving the old H.264 file while the user is stuck with the mp4v version somehow. The real issue might be that the browser can't decode the video despite having the right headers, so let me just swap the source to the Big Buck Bunny video and add some debugging to check the video's readyState and networkState properties. Actually, thinking about this more—the error message shows the path is `/video/demo.mp4`, but I changed it to an external URL, so either the user hasn't refreshed the page yet or they're looking at a cached version.\n\nLet me just walk through what's happening: the new code should be running with the external video URL, so if the user clears their cache and refreshes, it should work. The \"not displayed\" message probably means the video element exists but hasn't started playing yet, which would explain why they see the error state briefly before the external video loads. the page loads, there might be a brief moment where the error state shows before the video starts playing. I should suggest they use the external URL instead and give it a moment to load. But honestly, the real issue here is that this is a demo environment—the synthetic video has cartoon people and the detection model is fairly basic anyway, so the results won't be particularly meaningful. Let me step back and figure out what would actually be useful: either finding a real construction site video, using a better detection approach, or just getting the system working properly. I think the most practical path forward is to make sure the Big Buck Bunny video loads correctly so we can validate the dashboard works, then we can swap in better video later.","thinkingSignature":"5e92c3a6db73c247335dd9ae24f74897989030793d1c529ee58a00e881110a50"},{"type":"text","text":"206 Partial Content nghĩa là video đang được serve đúng. Không hiển thị có thể do trình duyệt. Thử refresh mạnh hoặc dùng trình duyệt khác.\n\nNhưng để chắc chắn, mình đổi sang dùng **URL video public** — không phụ thuộc vào server:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x084c7ffxc2k_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/frontend/src/App.jsx","edits":[{"oldText":"const API_BASE = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE || ''\n// Video: public internet URL (H.264, browser-compatible)\nconst VIDEO_URL = 'https://test-videos.co.uk/vids/bigbuckbunny/mp4/h264/720/Big_Buck_Bunny_720_10s_1MB.mp4'","newText":"const API_BASE = import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE || ''\n// Video: public CDN URL — bypasses all server-side issues\nconst VIDEO_URL = 'https://vjs.zencdn.net/v/oceans.mp4'"}]}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":130,"output":1125,"cacheRead":64383,"cacheWrite":934,"totalTokens":66572,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776792703111,"responseId":"0636e7800bfdad2c3475dbe08abab7b1"}}
