.countNonZero(mog_binary) / max(gray.size, 1)\n+164         mot_pct = cv2.countNonZero(motion_mask) / max(gray.size, 1)\n 164 \n-165         # Clean up\n+166         # If MOG2 thinks >60% is foreground, it's broken (new scene) — use motion instead\n+167         if mog_pct > 0.6:\n+168             combined = motion_mask\n+169         else:\n+170             combined = cv2.bitwise_or(mog_binary, motion_mask)\n+171 \n 166         kernel = cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE, (5, 5))\n 167         combined = cv2.morphologyEx(combined, cv2.MORPH_OPEN, kernel, iterations=1)\n 168         combined = cv2.morphologyEx(combined, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel, iterations=2)\n 169         return combined\n     ...","firstChangedLine":145},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776795459015}}
{"type":"message","id":"a2111813","parentId":"3269152b","timestamp":"2026-04-21T18:17:52.900Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now, the fundamental issue is that the synthetic video has very little motion (the workers move slowly side to side) and the MOG2 model might not pick them up well. For a demo system, the most important thing is to show detection on real footage.\n\nLet me take a step back and think about this differently:\n\n1. The current detector works fine for real webcam/video footage where there are actual people moving\n2. The synthetic demo video is just for show - and it's a difficult case for computer vision because it's animated graphics\n3. The key improvement needed is: for the Flask `/api/detect-frame` endpoint, the detector should warm up the background model first (process a few frames before detecting)\n\n\n4. For the video processor, I'll initialize the detector's background model by feeding it the first few frames before starting actual detection, which should help it build a better baseline for distinguishing people from the static background.\n\nNow I'm realizing the real bottleneck might be that frame differencing alone won't work for the demo since there's barely any motion, and the MOG2 model needs around 50 frames to stabilize—way more than the 15-20 frames the warm-up is doing.\n\nI should consider dropping background subtraction entirely and just detect based on skin color and vertical shapes instead, since the demo video is synthetic anyway. The catch is that this approach might fail on real footage with complex backgrounds, so maybe the best move is to keep MOG2 for real video but fall back to skin+shape detection for cases where motion detection doesn't help. Or I could tune MOG2 specifically for the synthetic demo by reducing history and increasing variance threshold to adapt faster.\n\nActually, the most practical solution is probably to let the video processor feed the first several frames through the detector to warm up the background model before actual detection starts, so when real people appear later, MOG2 can distinguish them from the learned background.","thinkingSignature":"9ef25eec61613c1dc8eafb5b7897f6ba35c6059b69d127081a6f4f0646882c05"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i55rfawi0lh7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'PYEOF'\nimport cv2, sys, numpy as np\nsys.path.insert(0, '/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/backend')\nfrom detector import PPEDetector\n\ndet = PPEDetector()\n\ncap = cv2.VideoCapture('/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/backend/demo.mp4')\n\n# Warm up with many frames\nfor i in range(40):\n    ret, f = cap.read()\n    if ret:\n        det._get_foreground(f)\n\n# Now detect\nfor i in range(5):\n    ret, f = cap.read()\n    if not ret: break\n    dets = det.detect_from_frame(f)\n    print(f\"Frame {40+i}: {len(dets)} people\")\n\ncap.release()\nPYEOF","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":76,"output":593,"cacheRead":117948,"cacheWrite":1794,"totalTokens":120411,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776795459068,"responseId":"0636f244fd8a62a8cc57f018945a40b4"}}
