{"type":"message","id":"4e580a3e","parentId":"33270a7c","timestamp":"2026-04-21T18:30:54.714Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent! At 720x480:- Demo video: 0.33s/frame, 3 people detected (correct!)\n- 4K upload: 0.48s/frame, 1 person detected\n\nWith FPS_TARGET=2 (0.5s interval):- Demo: 0.33s < 0.5s → CAN keep up! ✅- 4K: 0.48s < 0.5s → CAN keep up! ✅\n\nThis is much better. The detection finds 3 people in the demo video (good!), and the processing is fast enough to keep up with the target FPS.Now let me restart the backend and test the full system. But I also need to check the `/api/frame` endpoint — since we're processing at 720x480 but storing the annotated frame at display resolution, it should work.Actually, wait — the `annotated` frame returned by `process_single_frame` is at 720x480 (the processing resolution). But we resize it to display resolution (1280x720) in the `_process_loop`. \n\nI'm verifying the scaling logic: the `_proc_scale` gets set to 1.0 for the 1280x720 demo video, which means when I divide the bounding box coordinates by this scale, they stay at the original resolution, then the annotated frame gets resized back to display dimensions. So the output dimensions should be correct. Now let me restart and test the backend.","thinkingSignature":"a8e57a2efe5d965ee056810573473ca3304ac21f846d42971e9b755fca615214"},{"type":"text","text":"**0.33s/frame — đủ nhanh để chạy real-time!** Demo video detect đúng 3 người. Restart backend:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xbknzf6m2lte_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"kill $(ps aux | grep \"python3 app.py\" | grep -v grep | awk '{print $2}') 2>/dev/null\nsleep 2\ncd /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/projects/s1-ppe-safety/backend && \\\nMONGO_URI=\"mongodb://localhost:27017\" MONGO_DB=\"ppe_safety\" DEBUG=\"false\" FPS_TARGET=\"2\" \\\npython3 app.py > /tmp/s1-backend.log 2>&1 &\necho \"Backend PID: $!\"\nsleep 5\ncurl -s http://localhost:5000/api/summar